<font color="#FF0000"> IMPACTS ON FAMILY RELATIONS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 23:05:08 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
More significant than long hair, sideburns, torn jeans and sandels was the strong emotions both my father and I held concerning the Vietnam War.  I was only fifteen years old when, in 1969, my father spoke of his extreme disappointment over not enlisting in service during WW II. I cried when he spoke of it.  At fifteen, seeing your father cry makes a big impression.  You see, it was a birth defect that prevented him from joining his buddies in the war in Europe.  He must have felt left out, excluded.  He remained at home in Omaha working in a bank office.  <br><br>
I felt no such regret when it came my time to enroll for the draft in 1972.  In fact, I wanted to ignore, or even better, avoid it.  My father noticed this aversion of mine, I think.  We never spoke about it, however.  Nor did I ever tell him that I was drafting a thesis explaining my religious reasons for &quot;conscientiously objecting&quot; the draft.  Today, a C.O. might be confused with a C.E.O.  But back in 1972, a conscientious objector was a repulsive individual in my father's eyes.  <br><br>
My father and I never came to blows over my non-involvment in Vietnam because in January of 1973, Richard Nixon announced the end of the draft.  I never had to confront the war, my fears or my father.
<p><code>--   (David A. Johnson) </code><p>


